\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Gotchas}

Here are two very common gotchas for you ...

\textbf{First:} The initializer syntax can only be used in constructors:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
void C::set(int a, int b)
    : x_(a), y_(b) // WRONG!!! Not a constructor!!!
{}
\end{consolethree}

\textbf{Second:} Order of initialization is the order of member
declaration:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// C.h
class C
{
public:
    C(int, int);
private:
    int avg_; // avg_ = average of x_, y_
    int x_, y_;
};
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// C.cpp
C::C(int a, int b)
    : x_(a), y_(b), avg_((x_ + y_) / 2)
    // OOPS ... avg_ is initialized BEFORE
    // x_ and y_!!! ... so avg_ contains garbage!!!
{}
\end{consolethree}

To fix this problem, either

(1) use \textit{a} and \textit{b} in the initialization of \textit{avg\_:}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// C.cpp
C::C(int a, int b)
    : x_(a), y_(b), avg_((a + b) / 2)
    // avg_ doesn't rely on x_ and y_, so it's safe
{}
\end{consolethree}

or

(2) declare \textit{avg\_} after \textit{x\_} and \textit{y\_} in the class
definition (after all, the \textit{avg\_} average should clearly be set
after \textit{x\_} and \textit{y\_}, right?!?!)

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// C.h
class C
{
public:
    C(int, int);
private:
    int x_, y_, avg_;
    // avg_ = average of x_, y_
};
\end{consolethree}


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Review: Inline Functions}

Review the notes on inline functions. The following is only a quick
recap.

Recall that an inline function is like a rubber stamp for a function:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
inline int max(int x, int y)
{
    return (x > y ? x : y);
}

int main()
{
    int z = max(1, 2);
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

This means that there is really no \textit{max()} function. Rather, at the
place where the inline function is called, C++ substitutes the code for
\textit{max()} so that the program compiled is:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
int main()
{
    int z = (1 > 2 ? 1 : 2);
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

Inline functions can speed up program execution since the act of making
a function call takes time.

The compiler can choose to ignore making a function an inline function
so that it becomes a real function. This can happen if the function is
too long.

For multi-file compilation, the \textit{whole} inline function must be in
the header file. You cannot have an inline prototype in the header file
and the definition of the body of the function in the implementation
file.


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Inline Methods}

The information in this section applies to inlining of methods and not
just constructors.

Class methods (i.e., member functions) can also be inlined.

To inline a class method, you can either:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Put the whole method inside the class definition.
\item Put the method definition in the header file prepended with
  \textit{inline}.
\end{enumerate}

First way:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.h
class Date
{
public:
    Date(int yyyy, int mm, int dd)
        : yyyy_(yyyy), mm_(mm), dd_(dd)
    {}
    ...
private:
    int yyyy_, mm_, dd_;
};
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.cpp
// Constructor is NOT here
\end{consolethree}

Second way:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.h
class Date
{
public:
    Date(int yyyy, int mm, int dd);
    ...
private:
    int yyyy_, mm_, dd_;
};

inline Date::Date(int yyyy, int mm, int dd)
    : yyyy_(yyyy), mm_(mm), dd_(dd)
{}
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.cpp
// Constructor is NOT here
\end{consolethree}

