\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Copy constructor}

Suppose you already have a \textit{Date} object \textit{date1}. You want to
create another \textit{Date} object, \textit{date2}, so that \textit{date2}
has the same values as \textit{date1}.

\textit{date2} is not a reference to date1 like this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date & date2 = date1;
\end{consolethree}

Rather, you want \textit{date2} to be an actual Date object with
its own member variables.

You can do this

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date2(date1.get_yyyy(), date1.get_mm(), date1.get_dd());
\end{consolethree}

using the constructor that accepts three integers. But ...

What a pain!

This is cleaner:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date2;
date2 = date1;
\end{consolethree}

But this means that \textit{date1} was first initialized to something that
I do not want, and \textit{then} I assign the values of \textit{date1} to
\textit{date2}. That's not efficient.

We can achieve a cleaner initialization if we define a constructor that
accepts a \textit{Date} object. In other words I would like to do this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date2(date1);
\end{consolethree}

The prototype looks like this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date(const Date &);
\end{consolethree}

Note that I'm passing by reference to make the parameter passing
efficient and since I don't intend to modify the parameter, I make it a
constant. I'm therefore passing by constant reference.

The implementation looks like this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.cpp
Date::Date(const Date & date)
    : yyyy_(date.yyyy_), mm_(date.mm_), dd_(date.dd_)
{}
\end{consolethree}

You can think of \textit{date2} as a clone of \textit{date1}. You can (and
should) think of the copy constructor as a cloning operation.

For any class \textit{C}, the \textbf{copy constructor} of that class is a
constructor with the following prototype:

\textit{C(const C \&);}

Think of the copy constructor as a \textbf{cloning operation} and the
intent is to copy values from one object to another.

\begin{ex}
Inline our \textit{Date} copy constructor.
\end{ex}


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Calling the copy constructor}

There are actually two different syntax for invoking the copy
constructor of a class \textit{C}:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
C obj2(obj1);
C obj2 = obj1;
\end{consolethree}

WARNING: The second syntax is calling the copy constructor, not the
assignment operator.

\textbf{Example.} Insert a print statement in the copy constructor of
\textit{Date}:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date(const Date & date)
    : yyyy_(date.yyyy_), mm_(date.mm_), dd_(date.dd_)
{
    std::cout << "Date::Date(const Date &)\n";
}
\end{consolethree}

and then execute this in \textit{main()}:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date1(2014, 12, 25);
Date date2(date1);
Date date3 = date1;
\end{consolethree}


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Default copy constructor}

If a copy constructor is not specified, your C++ compiler will supply a
default copy constructor that initializes all instance variables of the
object invoking the constructor with the corresponding members of the
object that is passed in.

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Default copy constructor for Date
Date::Date(const Date & date)
    : yyyy_(date.yyyy_), mm_(date.mm_), dd_(date.dd_)
{}
\end{consolethree}

So technically we don't need the copy constructor for our \textit{Date}
class. However, you will see very soon, that there are cases (many
cases!!!) where you want your own copy constructor to do something else.
So here's the warning just so you catch it ...

\textbf{WARNING:} There are cases where the default member-by-member
copy is \textbf{\textit{not}} what you want. (See later examples.)

If you define a copy constructor, of course the compiler will not supply
one. You can't possibly have two copy constructors. (Why?)

Comment out our copy constructor in \textit{Date} and then execute in
\textit{main()}:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date1(2014, 12, 25);
Date date2(date1);
date2.print();
\end{consolethree}

You will find that the compiler will not complain and the program does
run. Why? Because your C++ compiler supplies the default copy
constructor.

